The thing you have to realise about divegrass is that it was originally a posh game which was played by "gentlemans' rules". In the public school days there were teams (like Corinthian) for example that would leave the goal open if they incurred a penalty because by their moral code they wouldn't cause an intentional foul.

What happens is that the sport completely breaks down when you play to win because so much of the law depends on good faith and playing fair. This is where simulation comes from - if you're diving, you're actually playing football optimally, same with drawing fouls.

It'll never change because football was never intended to be a professional sport and only became one by accident.

His statistics don't tell the whole story. Sure, he has scored a lot of goals and racked up a lot of assists, but he has also played for one of the best teams in the world for his entire career. This means that he has had the benefit of playing with top-quality players who have helped create scoring opportunities for him.
He has never truly shone on the international stage. Despite his impressive club career, Messi has never been able to replicate his success with the Argentine national team. He has come up short in major tournaments, including the World Cup, where he has failed to deliver the goods when it matters most.
His playstyle is one-dimensional. Let's face it, Messi is a one-trick pony. He is an incredible dribbler and can score amazing goals, but he lacks the physicality and tactical awareness to be a truly complete player.
In conclusion, while Messi may have impressive statistics and undeniable talent, he is far from the world-beater that many make him out to be. In my opinion, he is extremely overrated and there are many other players who deserve more recognition for their contributions to the beautiful game.

Being "Slavic" doesn't really mean anything including in Croatia. Obviously our language is Slavic and we have Slavic influences especially in the north. Croats without autism will identify as Croatian, Catholic, and "Central European" or Western.

But genetically and culturally Croatia is a few centimeters away from Italy while being miles away from Poland or Russia. So calling us "Slavic" is misleading.

This obviously also depends on the region in Croatia. The north is obviously more Slavic and less Med and has a lot in common with Slovenia, Austria, or Hungary.

But the Croats from Istria, Dalmatia, and Herzegovina/Bosnia have very little genetically or culturally that you would identify as "Slavic" except for the language.

I am not going to produce genetic studies to "prove" this because I do not have enough autism but I have dealt with many people from all over Europe and the differences between Croats and other Slavs are simply vast
